Executive Summary

	The Gaming Room wants to expand its game, Draw It or Lose It, from being an Android-only app into a web based application that can run across multiple platforms. The main goal of the project is to create a system that allows multiple teams and players to join games while keeping everything organized and running smoothly. The application also needs to make sure game names and team names are unique and that only one instance of the game service exists in memory at a time.
	To solve these problems, the application will use object oriented programming principles and software design patterns. The singleton pattern will make sure only one GameService object exists, while the iterator pattern will help search through games, teams, and players efficiently. The project will also use inheritance with a shared Entity class to reduce duplicate code and make the application easier to manage and update later.
	The recommended solution is to develop the game as a web based distributed application using Java and a Linux server environment. Linux is a strong option because it is reliable, secure, scalable, and works well for hosting web applications. This design will allow The Gaming Room to support users across different devices and operating systems while keeping the application flexible for future updates and improvements.

Requirements

The Gaming Room wants to expand Draw It or Lose It from an Android only game into a web based application that can support multiple platforms and devices. The application must allow one or more teams to participate in a game, and each team can contain multiple players. The system also needs to ensure that game names and team names are unique so users do not accidentally create duplicates.
Another important requirement is that only one instance of the GameService class can exist in memory at one time. This will allow the application to manage all games, teams, and players from a single service. The system must also generate unique identifiers for each game, team, and player object that is created.
From a technical standpoint, the application should be scalable, secure, and able to operate in a distributed web based environment. The design should support multiple operating systems and devices while maintaining good performance and reliability. The application should also follow object oriented programming principles and use software design patterns to improve organization, efficiency, and maintainability.

Design Constraints

One major design constraint for the Draw It or Lose It application is that the system must operate in a distributed web based environment that supports multiple platforms and devices. Because users may access the game from Windows, Mac, Linux, or mobile devices, the application must remain compatible across different operating systems and screen sizes. This requires developers to focus on portability and responsive design during development.
Another design constraint is the requirement that only one instance of the GameService class can exist in memory at a time. To solve this issue, the singleton design pattern is used to control how objects are created and accessed throughout the application. This helps maintain consistency across the system and prevents duplicate game services from being created.
The application must also ensure that game names and team names are unique. This creates additional processing requirements because the system must search through existing collections before adding new games, teams, or players. The iterator pattern helps solve this issue by allowing the application to efficiently loop through stored objects and check for duplicate names.
Performance and scalability are also important constraints because the application may eventually support many users at the same time. The software must be able to manage multiple games, teams, and players without slowing down or crashing. Security is another important factor because user information and game data must be protected across networks and devices.
Finally, the development team must consider cost, maintenance, and long term support when selecting tools and operating platforms. Choosing Java as the programming language helps solve many compatibility issues because Java applications can run on multiple operating systems using the Java Virtual Machine.


System Architecture View

