The Draw It or Lose It application will use a distributed web based architecture that allows users to connect from different devices and operating systems through a network connection. The application will use a client server model where users access the game through client devices while the main application logic and storage are managed on the server side. This structure allows the system to support multiple users at the same time while maintaining performance, scalability, and centralized data management. 


Domain Model

	The UML class diagram for The Gaming Room application shows how the different classes work together to support the Draw It or Lose It game. The diagram is designed using object oriented programming principles to create a system that is organized, reusable, and easy to maintain.
	The Entity class acts as the base class for the application. It contains the common attributes shared by the other classes, including the id and name fields. The Game, Team, and Player classes all inherit from Entity, which demonstrates the object oriented principle of inheritance. By using inheritance, the application avoids duplicate code and keeps shared functionality centralized in one class.
	The Game class represents a game instance and contains a list of Team objects. Each game can have multiple teams assigned to it. The Team class contains a list of Player objects, allowing multiple players to belong to a team. This relationship demonstrates composition because games are made up of teams and teams are made up of players.
	The GameService class manages the application data and controls the creation of games, teams, and players. This class uses the singleton design pattern, which ensures that only one instance of GameService exists in memory at a time. This supports the client requirement that only one game service instance can manage the application data. The GameService class also handles unique identifiers for games, teams, and players by using incrementing ID values.
	The iterator pattern is used in methods such as addGame(), addTeam(), and addPlayer(). Before creating a new object, the system searches existing collections to verify that names are unique. This fulfills the client requirement that game names and team names cannot be duplicated.
	The ProgramDriver class is responsible for running the application, while the SingletonTester class is used to test that the singleton pattern works correctly. Together, the classes in the UML diagram create a structured design that supports scalability, maintainability, and efficient game management for a web based distributed environment.


 

